Kaggle Competition - Cover Type¶

Kaggle user name and final performance

  • Identidication

    Kaggle name : matthieu Student : Matthieu Roussel)

  • Final scores :

    Python Notebook Final Score under Kaggle : 0.95711

    Important : best Databricks Score under Kaggle voer the 30% sample : 0.92368

Overall approach

The overall approach was for me to test a lot of approaches :

  1. Simple straight ahead pipeline,
  2. Tuning the hyperparameters by cv
  3. Try a lot of the available multiclass classifiers
  4. Try a few data transformations
  5. Try some blending of models

I have tried many model types and approches, starting with simple pipelines + tuning in Databricks and then trying the further approaches as presented in this notebook. The aim was to test a lot of different techniques, finding inspiration in documentations and online examples. I have presented here a good part of the whole process here, keeping track of major attempts. The work does not reflect the exhaustivity of the multiple attempts tuning the hyperparamters, trying with smaller train samples ; approches degrading the results (unsuccessfull attempts to tune an MLP, reencode one encoders in one variable) have been discard.

In all approaches, I always kept a % for testing before submitting (varying from 30% to 5%).

In more details :

  1. Databricks attempts

    I have tryed very hard to stick with Databricks on this challenge.

    I obtained with a litle efforts an accuracy of 0.87 using a random forest (max_depth 25, number of trees : 30), tuned with gridsearch on the 2 mentioned parameters. This first "encouraging" result was obtained after attempts of fine tuning of multinomial logistic regression (regParam) and decision trees.

    I then tried hard to get above 0,87 by tuning the hyperparameters of the random forest (max_depth, number of trees, maxBins, minInstancesPerNode, impurity, featureSubsetStrategy) , generating more complexe trees (number of trees and other parameters). I than started to run into severe problems : using grid parameters, the cluster just kept shutting down after 15 to 30 minutes of processing. I encountered memory errors with the java garbage collector ("GC overhead limit exceeded"), wich could not be resolved with the community version.

    As soon as the number of trees got above 50 or 75 (with a tradeoff with max_depth value), the problem occured. I tried than to run single attemps, or simple split test/validation runs. The only solution was for me to reduce the training set consequently, degrading then the overall performances.

    After spending a lot of time to try to fine tune the model under Databricks, I got very frustrated and decided to make attemps under regluar python notebook, presented here.

  1. Python approach under notebook

    A lot of diffrent approches, not always efficient :

    • Initial simple model
    • Tuning hyperparameters
    • Feature engineering : a few simple transformations applied
    • Second run of models (initial, fine tuning) with these features, with few improvements
    • I decide to try to reduce the demensions of the wilderness area and soil flags. I builded a submodel based on the soil type and wilderness area flags making a weak but stable model/subscore for the one variables (0,64 accuracy); I then just used the probability of each class as new features.
    • I then ran again in the overall process, sticking with random forrest at first. I tried few other metods (extra trees, xgbost) with a minimal tuning. I wanted to avoid long treatments for very small gain. Overall, integrating the ones scores to the final model lead to a very small complementary increase of accuracy.

I should have further more try to replace the few abnormal values in shading but did not invest time on this.

  1. Back to Databricks

    I went back to Databricks, and tried this time to fine tune simple decision trees classifier. In a logic of improvement, I tryed as I did here to build a one vs rest model using the decision tree calssifers and my fine tuning (maxdepth : 30, MaxBins : 40, minInstancesPerNode=5). It lead me to my final "Databricks" accuracy of 0.92368. I submitted that one to to Kaggle (but not for the final results). The only feature engeneering I did further more was to decode the "onehotencoders" variable into single catégorical variables : one for wilderness and one for soil type.

def features_importances(estimator, col_array, title):
    f_i = estimator.feature_importances_
    ix = np.argsort(f_i)[::-1]
    print("%s Main important features\n" % (title))
    for f in range(20):
        print("%d. %s (%f)" % (f + 1, col_array.columns[ix[f]], f_i[ix[f]]))
    print("\nMean Feature Importance %.6s" % (np.mean(f_i)))
    ix=ix[:20]
    plt.figure(1, figsize=(15, 5))
    plt.title("Main features importances")
    plt.bar(range(20), f_i[ix], color="silver", align="center") 
    plt.xticks(range(20), col_array.columns[ix], fontsize=12, rotation=90) 
    plt.xlim([-1, 20])
    plt.show()

Feature engineering

Since I had tested under Databricks several multiclass algorithms, I then wanted to try to improve the information provided by the main features, back into the same model at this stage (random forest) for comparison.
  • Computing features

Since distances and elevation contributed to almost 2 thirds of the model, I first tried to build features derived from these main distances features, calculating difference and sums betwen the features.

I first wanted to test the impact of integrating these simple features transformations, wich has revealed to be significative. I kept these variables but should have done some further invistigations to understanding non linear relations lying betwen dome variables. I am shure a complementary improvements are possible. I did not take the requiered time for doing this.

In [24]:
df_train_train_mod = df_train_train
df_train_test_mod = df_train_test
In [25]:
def tranformations(df):
    # Combining features with simple transformations.
    df["dist_combo_1"] = df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Hydrology'] + df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Fire_Points']
    df["dist_combo_2"] = abs(df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Hydrology'] - df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Fire_Points'])
    df["dist_combo_3"] = abs(df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Hydrology'] + df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Roadways'])
    df["dist_combo_4"] = abs(df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Hydrology'] - df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Roadways'])
    df["dist_combo_5"] = abs(df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Fire_Points'] + df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Roadways'])
    df["dist_combo_6"] = abs(df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Fire_Points'] - df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Roadways'])
    df["dist_combo_7"] = abs(df['Elevation'] - df['Vertical_Distance_To_Hydrology'])
    df["Mean_Distances1"] = (df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Fire_Points'] + df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Hydrology'] \
          + df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Roadways'])/3        
    df["Mean_Distances2"] = (df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Fire_Points'] + df['Horizontal_Distance_To_Hydrology'])/2   
    # Put back cover_type as the last variable 
    cols = list(df.columns.values)
    cols.pop(cols.index('Cover_Type'))
    df = df[cols+['Cover_Type']] 
    return df

Optimizing One hot encoders

My idea was initially to reduce the number of variables used in one hot encoders, trying to capture the relevant information they could endebb. I choose SVC to build a subscore, with the aim to use the probability of belonging to each class (7 variables) as new input variables, in replacement of all the one encoders corresponding to soil types and wilderness area. Note : considering the computation cost (complexity more than quadratic), I ran the learning algorithm over a more concise sample to ensure convergeance. The model has been trained tuning gamma, C, and the kernel type (finally sigmoïd matched best)

def add_df_from_svm(df,res):
    for i in range(7):
        df['prob_'+str(i+1)]=res[:,i:(i+1)]
    # move cover_type to last column
    cols = list(df.columns.values)
    cols.pop(cols.index('Cover_Type'))
    df = df[cols+['Cover_Type']] 
    return df
